<LP>
   THE U.S. PENSION-INSURANCE agency can force LTV Corp. to
reassume liability for more than $2 billion in pension
benefits that the company stopped funding in 1987, the
Supreme Court ruled. The decision could save the troubled
agency billions of dollars and hinder LTV's exit from Chapter
11 proceedings.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices plunged in thin trading amid skepticism about
corporate earnings and interest rates. The Dow Jones
Industrial Average dropped 53.71 points to close at 2882.18.
Bond prices also fell on further fallout from some bad
economic news. The dollar sagged against most other
currencies.
   ---
   The SEC received its third court setback in recent weeks
as the Supreme Court let stand a ruling that the CFTC, and
not the SEC, has the authority to regulate stock "baskets."
The CFTC repeated its offer to expedite approval of the
products.
   ---
   Motorola is being ordered to stop selling its best-selling
microchip in a patent dispute with Hitachi. The move could
hurt Apple and other U.S. computer firms, as well as
Motorola.
   ---
   An exception in patent law for drugs also applies to
medical devices, the Supreme Court ruled. The decision is a
defeat for medical-technology developers with long-held
patents and a victory for newer companies.
   ---
   Donald Trump moved closer to an accord with lenders under
which he would borrow an additional $60 million and suspend
interest payments on other loans. Three New Jersey banks
tentatively agreed to participate.
                                                                                                       

   The Trump Shuttle plans to scrap more than 25% of its
Saturday flights plus four Sunday round trips.
   ---
   Occidental Petroleum's debt and preferred stock were
downgraded by S&amp;P, which cited the company's high fixed
costs, heavy dividend demands and expected weak earnings.
   ---
   NWA is expected to name Frederick Rentschler to be the
Northwest Air parent's chief executive. Rentschler is
currently chief at Beatrice, which is merging with ConAgra.
   ---
   Export licenses will no longer be required for shipments
of most high-technology goods to U.S. allies, the Commerce
Department announced.
   ---
   Chrysler is holding "intensified" talks with Fiat about a
potential alliance in which the Italian firm may help
Chrysler develop new models.
   ---
   Prudential-Bache agreed to sell its Canadian retail
brokerage business to Burns Fry. The U.S. securities firm
intends to shift most of its other Canadian operations to New
York.
   ---
   CMS Energy's 49%-owned cogeneration venture entered a $2.3
billion sale-leaseback accord involving its Midland, Mich.,
power plant. CMS also formed a new partnership to possibly
expand the facility.
   ---
   Bankers Trust laid off 75 professionals in its flagship
bank's corporate finance department, reflecting the slump in
mergers and acquisitions.
   ---
   Eight companies were sued by the federal government for
allegedly polluting waters off Southern California.
   ---
   First Boston replaced its junk-bond chief and reassigned
other aides amid a deep slump in its bond business.
   ---
   Corn and soybean futures prices rose in the wake of heavy
rains over the weekend in the Midwest.
   ---
   Henry Ansbacher's controlling shareholders plan to sell
their 61.6% stake in the British merchant bank.
